## ENTITY HIERARCHY — read this so you don't confuse the four "order/wave" concepts

The business flows through four distinct levels. They have similar names but are NOT the same thing:
1. Client Order — what a client placed; can contain many models/sizes/quantities. Identified by CDNO (a field on EXP_DET). There is no separate "orders" table.
2. Expedition — groups one or more client orders going to the SAME client at the SAME address. Identified by EXPNO. Tables: EXP_ENT (header) + EXP_DET (lines).
3. Preparation Order — created from a SINGLE expedition, up to 24 pairs. Identified by ORDNO. Tables: ORD_ENT (header) + ORD_DET (lines).
4. Picking Wave — built from one or more preparation orders (possibly from different expeditions), up to 24 pairs; this is what an operator physically picks. Identified by VAGNO. Detailed in VAG_DET, and referenced on ORD_DET.

So: "order number" is ambiguous. CDNO = client order; ORDNO = preparation order. When a user just says "order," assume the preparation order (ORDNO) unless they clearly mean the client's original order.

## DATABASE SCHEMA

**EXP_ENT — Expedition headers**
- EXPNO — Expedition number (unique)
- STATUS — 5 = Completed, 9 = Cancelled
- USERCRDH — Creation date
- ADRCOD — Client's address code
- ADRTIERS — The client (customer)

**EXP_DET — Expedition line details (one line per article)**
- EXPNO — Links to EXP_ENT
- DETNO — Detail/line number within the expedition (increments per article)
- CDNO — Client order number (the original order the client placed — NOT the preparation order)
- REF — Product reference (e.g. 5700GT)
- SREF1 — Product width
- SREF2 — Product size, US format (e.g. 8, 8.5, 9, 12)
- QTE — Quantity to ship
- USERCRDH — Line creation date
- BLMOD — Carrier shipping this expedition

**ORD_ENT — Preparation order headers**
- ORDNO — Preparation order ID (incremental, unique)
- STATUS — 4 or 5 = Completed, 9 = Cancelled
- USERCRDH — Creation date
- ORDCTRL — User who controlled/verified the preparation order
- ORDUSER — User who did the packing

**ORD_DET — Preparation order line details**
- ORDNO — Links to ORD_ENT (preparation order)
- LNNO — Line number within the preparation order
- EXPNO — Expedition this line belongs to (links to EXP_ENT/EXP_DET)
- DETNO — Links to the expedition detail line (with EXPNO)
- VAGNO — The picking wave this line is assigned to
- VAGLNNO — Line number within the wave
- VAGUSER — User who PICKED the wave
- STATUS_VAG — Line status within the wave: 2 = Completed, 9 = Cancelled
- REF / SREF1 / SREF2 — Product reference, width, size
- QTE — Quantity to pick (planned)
- QTE_RAM — Quantity actually PICKED (can be less than QTE if an item couldn't be found)
- QTE_COL — Quantity SHIPPED (always equals QTE_RAM)

**VAG_DET — Picking wave movement details (who/what/when/where)**
- VAGNO — Picking wave number (0 = this movement was NOT for a wave; exclude these for wave analysis)
- MVNO — Movement ID (incremental); a movement can contain one or more articles
- MVLG — Movement line (identifies each line within a movement)
- REF / SREF1 / SREF2 / QTE — The product being moved and quantity
- CTN — Carton identifier (populated depending on what is moved)
- NUN — Unit identifier (populated depending on what is moved)
- LOC_ORI — Origin location (e.g. H-06-13)
- LOC_DES — Destination location (e.g. C-022)
- USERCR — User who moved the items (the picker)
- USERCRDH — Movement timestamp

## HOW THE TABLES JOIN
- Wave: ORD_DET.VAGNO = VAG_DET.VAGNO
- Preparation order: ORD_DET.ORDNO = ORD_ENT.ORDNO
- Expedition: ORD_DET.EXPNO = EXP_ENT.EXPNO = EXP_DET.EXPNO
- Expedition detail line: (ORD_DET.EXPNO, ORD_DET.DETNO) = (EXP_DET.EXPNO, EXP_DET.DETNO)
- Customer of a line: ORD_DET.EXPNO -> EXP_ENT.EXPNO -> EXP_ENT.ADRTIERS
- Product identity across tables: REF (+ SREF1 width, SREF2 size)

## DATA VALUE NOTES (so your filters and groupings are correct)
- CUSTOMER = ADRTIERS. One ADRTIERS can have several ADRCOD address codes, so for any per-customer figure GROUP BY "ADRTIERS" — never ADRCOD, which splits one customer across its addresses.
- ROLES are different fields, do not conflate them: the wave PICKER is VAGUSER (ORD_DET) / USERCR (VAG_DET); the PACKER is ORD_ENT.ORDUSER; the CONTROLLER is ORD_ENT.ORDCTRL.
- QUANTITIES: QTE = planned, QTE_RAM = actually picked, QTE_COL = shipped (always = QTE_RAM). For "picked"/"collected" use QTE_RAM (or QTE_COL); for "ordered/planned" use QTE.
- SREF1 (width) is stored as short codes such as REG, W, NR, MEN, and may be blank — NOT the words "WIDE"/"NARROW". Run SELECT DISTINCT "SREF1" if unsure.
- VAG_DET.VAGNO = 0 means the movement was not part of a wave; exclude it (WHERE "VAGNO" <> 0) for wave-level analysis.
- Text fields are trimmed, so exact matches like WHERE "LOC_ORI" = 'H-06-13' work.
- Dates (USERCRDH) are timestamps; use date functions or range filters for time-based questions.

## BUSINESS RULES
- A preparation order is created from a single expedition, max 24 pairs.
- A picking wave is built from one or more preparation orders, max 24 pairs; a wave with fewer than 24 pairs is under-filled.
- QTE_RAM/QTE_COL may differ from QTE if there were stock issues (an item could not be found).
- Warehouse locations follow Zone-Aisle-Shelf format (e.g. H-06-13 = Zone H, Aisle 06, Shelf 13).

